<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="practical-identifying-mitosis-in-plant-cells">Practical: Identifying Mitosis in Plant Cells</h2><ul><li><p>Growth in plants occurs in specific regions called <span class="popovers" data-content="Undifferentiated plant cells that form in the vegetative organs of a plant. They can differentiate into different specialised cells." data-title="Meristem" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">meristems</span></p></li><li><p>The root tip meristem can be used to study <b>mitosis</b></p></li><li><p>The root tip meristem can be found <b>just behind the protective root cap</b></p></li><li><p>In the root tip meristem, there is a<b> zone of cell division</b> that contains cells undergoing <b>mitosis</b></p></li><li><p>Pre-prepared slides of root tips can be studied or temporary slides can be prepared using the <b>squash technique</b> (root tips are <b>stained</b> and then <b>gently squashed</b>, spreading the cells out into a thin sheet and allowing individual cells undergoing mitosis to be clearly seen)</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Micrograph showing a stained root tip" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="671" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-stained-root-tip.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>A micrograph of a stained root tip, nuclei are clearly visible</b></i></p><h4 id="apparatus">Apparatus</h4><ul><li><p>Roots of onion or garlic</p></li><li><p>Microscope slide</p></li><li><p>Cover skip</p></li><li><p>1 M hydrochloric acid</p></li><li><p>Stain (acetic orcein, toluidine blue for example)</p></li><li><p>Paper towel</p></li><li><p>Scalpel blade</p></li><li><p>Cutting tile</p></li><li><p>Water bath at 60<sup>o</sup>C</p></li><li><p>Boiling tube</p></li><li><p>Optical microscope</p></li></ul><h4 id="method">Method</h4><ol start="1"><li><p><b>Garlic</b> or <b>onion</b> (<i>Allium cepa</i>) root tips are most commonly used (the bulbs can be encouraged to grow roots by suspending them over water for a week or two)</p></li><li><p>Prepare a boiling tube of 1M hydrochloric acid and place in a water bath at 60<sup>o</sup>C for 10 minutes</p></li><li><p>Remove the <b>tips</b> of the roots (about 1cm) and place in the <b>warmed hydrochloric acid </b>for 5 minutes</p></li><li><p>Rinse the tips well in cold water using a pipette and blot dry with a paper towel </p></li><li><p>Cut approximately 2mm off the tip and place onto a microscope slide</p></li><li><p>Add a drop of a suitable <b>stain</b> (eg. warm, acetic orcein, which stains chromosomes a deep purple)</p></li><li><p>The stained root tip is <b>gently squashed</b> on a <b>glass slide</b> using a blunt instrument (eg. the handle of a mounting needle or a cover slip using your fist to gently apply pressure in a rolling motion)</p></li><li><p>View the slide under the microscope</p></li><li><p>Cells undergoing mitosis (similar to those in the images below) can be seen and drawn</p></li><li><p>Annotations can then be added to these drawings to show the <b>different stages of mitosis</b></p></li></ol><h4 id="results">Results</h4><ul><li><p>You should be able to observe cells in different stages of mitosis from the stained meristem </p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Micrograph showing a cell undergoing prophase (P)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="690" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/10/Micrograph-showing-a-cell-undergoing-prophase-P.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemy